# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1877-louisville-grays-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1876-louisville-grays-season] The **Louisville Grays** were formed prior to the 1876 Major League Baseball season and joined the just formed National League as a charter member.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1876-louisville-grays-season] They finished in fifth place in their debut season under manager Jack Chapman.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] The **1877 Boston Red Caps season** was the seventh season of the franchise.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-boston-red-caps-season] Arthur Soden became the new owner of the franchise, who won their first National League pennant.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-brooklyn-hartfords-season] The Hartford Dark Blues moved to Brooklyn, New York prior to the 1877 season and were renamed as the **Brooklyn Hartfords**.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-brooklyn-hartfords-season] This was to be the Hartfords' last season, as they disbanded following the completion of their schedule.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1877 Chicago White Stockings season** was the 6th season of the Chicago White Stockings franchise, the 2nd in the National League and the fourth at 23rd Street Grounds.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings finished fifth in the National League with a record of 26–33.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The **1877 Cincinnati Reds season** was the team's second season in the National League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team finished sixth and last in the league with a record of 15–42, 25½ games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] After finishing dead last in the National League in the 1876 season, the Reds attempted to improve their club by signing Lip Pike, who spent the previous season with the St.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike was also named the manager of the team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The Reds got off to another terrible start, as they had a 3–11 start to the season, and Pike stepped down as the manager.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] The team was briefly disbanded by owner Josiah Keck, and although a group of eight businessmen stepped in to rescue the franchise, some Cincinnati players had been signed by other teams in the interim, and some newspapers subsequently refused to list the Red's results.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Bob Addy took over as player manager; however, he too saw very few wins as Cincinnati went 5–19 during his managerial stint.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Jack Manning then finished the year as player-manager, going 7–12, as the Reds had a 15–42 record and once again finished in the National League cellar, 25.5 games behind the first place Boston Red Caps.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Charley Jones had another solid season for the Reds, hitting .310 with two homers and a team high 36 RBI.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Manning also had a solid year, hitting .317, as he had a team high 80 hits while tying Jones with a team high 36 RBI.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] Pike hit .298 with a team high four home runs, and added 23 RBI.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-cincinnati-reds-season] On the mound, rookie Bobby Mitchell came up late in the season and was very impressive, leading Cincinnati with six victories and a team best 3.51 ERA in twelve games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The **1877 Louisville Grays scandal** was an incident in which members of the Louisville Grays baseball team accepted money to lose games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Four players – Bill Craver, Jim Devlin, George Hall and Al Nichols – were subsequently banned from professional baseball for life.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In the early days of professional baseball, crooked play was not uncommon, and many players were suspected of throwing games in exchange for money.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Illegal influence by gamblers had undermined the National Association of Professional Base Ball Players (NA) in the early 1870s, and William Hulbert formed the National League (NL) in 1876 with the intention of driving it out of the game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nevertheless, there were still several gambling-related scandals during the 1876 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Jim Devlin started his baseball career in 1873 and was the Louisville Grays' pitcher in 1876 and 1877.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1876 he had a win–loss record of 30–35 and an earned run average of 1.56, while leading the league in complete games, innings pitched and strikeouts.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, Devlin went 35–25 with a 2.25 ERA and again led the league in complete games and innings pitched.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started and completed each of the Grays' 61 games, an accomplishment no other pitcher in history has matched.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Outfielder George Hall was one of the best sluggers in the game's early history.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After playing in the NA from 1871 to 1875, he joined the Philadelphia Athletics in 1876.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] That season, he led the league with five home runs and finished second in batting average, on-base percentage, slugging percentage and total bases.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In 1877, he played for the Grays and had a .323 batting average.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Shortstop Bill Craver was a noted crooked player who had been expelled from a previous team for throwing games in 1870.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He played for the New York Mutuals in 1876 before joining the Grays the following season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Al Nichols also played for the Mutuals in 1876.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He joined the Grays in the middle of the 1877 season on the recommendation of Hall and appeared in six games for the team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Newspapers named the players "Terror" Devlin, "Gentleman George" Hall, "Butcher" Craver and "Slippery Elm" Nichols".
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] After the games of August 13, 1877, the Grays were in first place by four games over St.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louis and 4.5 over the Boston Red Caps, with a record of 27 wins and 13 losses, and with some 20 games left to play.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They then commenced a nine-game winless streak (including one tie) and eventually lost the championship to Boston.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] They won six out of their last seven, making their season record of 35-25 look reasonably respectable, but those wins came after Boston had clinched the pennant, having won 20 of their final 21 games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Louisville finished second, seven games behind Boston.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Chase received telegrams informing him of suspicious gambling activity involving the team.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] He started an investigation, and Devlin and Hall confessed to throwing several exhibition games late in the season, with Devlin receiving up to $100 per game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 4, the entire team was gathered, and Chase demanded that they turn over their telegrams.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Every player except Craver complied, and the telegrams showed that Devlin, Hall and Nichols had thrown games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] On October 30, Craver, Devlin, Hall and Nichols were expelled from the club, and on December 4, the NL banned them from professional baseball for the rest of their lives.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The Grays franchise folded after the 1877 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Over the next few decades, there were fewer suspicions of game-fixing in professional baseball.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] The four banned players were never reinstated.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Nichols played semi-professional baseball, Craver and Devlin became police officers, and Hall worked as an engraver and clerk.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Devlin tried to be reinstated many times but was unsuccessful.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] In one instance, he got on his knees and begged Hulbert for another chance.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] Hulbert responded by handing him $50 (roughly equivalent to $1,200 in 2017 value) and saying, "Devlin, that's what I think of you personally; but, damn you, you have sold a game; you are dishonest and this National League will not stand for it." Devlin died of tuberculosis in 1883.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-scandal] His 1.90 career ERA is the third-lowest of all-time among pitchers with at least 1,000 innings pitched.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] The **1877 Louisville Grays** were the victim of Major League Baseball's first gambling scandal.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] Pitcher Jim Devlin, outfielder George Hall, utility player Al Nichols and shortstop Bill Craver were accused of throwing games at the end of the season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] All four were banned from baseball for life.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] The team was unable to continue and folded after the season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] After a spectacular start that included a 27–13 record to begin the season, the Grays mysteriously lost seven games in a row.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] Players bobbled the ball, seemed to slow between bases, and swung suspiciously wide.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-louisville-grays-season] The result was that the Grays lost the pennant.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The **1877 major league baseball season** was contested from April 30 through October 6, 1877, and saw the Boston Red Caps as the pennant winner of the second season of the National League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Over the off-season, in December 1876, two teams were formally kicked out of the league for failing to fulfill their schedules: New York Mutuals and Philadelphia Athletics, contracting the league from eight to six teams.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Hartford Dark Blue would relocate from Hartford, Connecticut to Brooklyn, New York, as the Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The 1877 schedule consisted of 60 games for all six teams of the National League.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 12 games against the other five teams in the league.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season that the National League adopted the format.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The format would last only through the following season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 30 featuring a game between the Boston Red Caps and Brooklyn Hartfords.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season was on October 6, featuring four teams.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] Three tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind occurred throughout the season (though standings were determined by total wins, not winning percentage).
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords had two tie games.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Boston Red Caps, Chicago White Stockings, Cincinnati Reds, and Louisville Grays had one tie game each.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Chicago White Stockings would play their final game at 23rd Street Grounds on October 6 against the Louisville Grays, moving to Lakefront Park for the start of the 1878 season.
[src:1877-louisville-grays-season/1877-major-league-baseball-season] The Brooklyn Hartfords hosted a neutral site game against the Chicago White Stockings on their last home game of the season, September 22, at the site of the former National Association's New Haven Elm Citys, at the Howard Avenue Grounds in New Haven, Connecticut.
